Reasoning: The paper discusses the transformation of bibliographic data into networks, which is a topic that falls under several sub-categories in computer science. The use of network multiplication and normalization techniques suggests that the paper may belong to the sub-categories of Social and Information Networks (cs.SI), Digital Libraries (cs.DL), and Systems and Control (cs.SY). The analysis of large datasets and the computation of network measures and communities suggest that the paper may also belong to the sub-categories of Information Retrieval (cs.IR) and Sound (cs.SD).
